Outcome: Total Charitable Giving (log_giving)
The PSID asks families separately how much they donated to four categories: religious organizations, the needy, health causes, and education. The code sums whichever of those four columns are available for a given wave, treating missing values as zero. Because giving is right-skewed (most families give little, a few give a lot), it's log-transformed using log1p(total_giving) — adding 1 before logging so that zero-giving families don't get dropped. The outcome is measured in the same wave as the move.

Treatment: moved
Derived from the PSID item "WHY MOVED 1ST." The logic is:

If the family reported any reason for moving (codes 1–9), moved = 1
If no reason was given, moved = 0
Sentinel non-responses (97/98/99 = Other/DK/Refused) are set to NA and dropped from estimation
This makes moved a binary indicator: did this family relocate between the prior wave and this one?

Moderator: religious_lag
This is a lagged version of whether the family reported any religious preference. The base indicator codes PSID denomination values 1–13 as 1 and codes 0 (none), 97, 98, 99 as 0. The lag is then computed within each family, sorted by wave — so religious_lag in wave t reflects the family's religious status in wave t-1, before the move happened.

The lag serves two purposes: (1) it establishes the moderator as pre-treatment, avoiding the concern that moving itself caused a change in religious identity, and (2) it tests whether pre-existing religious attachment conditions how much giving responds to a move (the hypothesis being that religious families may lose congregation ties when they move).

Controls: Fixed Effects and Weights
Family fixed effects (family_key): Each family serves as its own control. This absorbs all stable, unobserved differences between families — income trajectory, personality, baseline generosity — and means the estimate of moved comes entirely from within-family variation over time (i.e., comparing a family in years when it moved vs. years when it didn't).

Wave fixed effects (wave): Absorbs any year-level shocks common to all families — economic recessions, tax-law changes affecting charitable deductions, COVID, etc.

PSID longitudinal family weights (family_weight): The PSID over-samples low-income households and loses some families to attrition over time. The longitudinal weights rebalance the sample so estimates reflect the broader U.S. population rather than the PSID's particular sampling design.

Together, the model is: within a given family, in a wave when they moved versus a wave when they didn't, how does giving change — and does that effect differ based on whether they were religious the wave before?




the analysis is entirely at the family/household level. The data loaded is psid_family_year_2001_latest.parquet, which is the family-level panel, not the individual file.

The only head-of-household characteristics that appear are:

head_age → used as age and age² controls, but only in Model 3 (the robustness spec), not the main models
head_sex and birth year → used only to construct family_key (the tracking identifier), not as regression controls
Religious_Preference → technically measured on the head, but treated as a family-level attribute
So in the core models (M1 and M2), there are no individual-level controls at all — the family fixed effect is doing the work of absorbing stable individual/family characteristics, and wave fixed effects handle time trends. Age only enters as an afterthought in M3 to check robustness.

This means things like individual income, education, employment status, or non-head household members' religiosity are not in the model. Whether that's a concern depends on your argument — if you're claiming family FEs absorb the stable confounders, then time-varying individual traits (job loss, retirement, etc.) that correlate with both moving and giving would be the main gap.

